I wanna also start with connecting providers

00:01:18.860 --> 00:01:19.779
to their patient data.

00:01:19.779 --> 00:01:23.620
So what am I talking about there and who rather?

00:01:23.620 --> 00:01:26.660
Specifically, I'm talking about in today's discussion,

00:01:27.500 --> 00:01:28.339
ambulatory providers.

00:01:28.339 --> 00:01:31.300
A lot of times when we start talking about healthcare,

00:01:31.300 --> 00:01:34.980
a lot of the papers you'll read, et cetera,

00:01:34.980 --> 00:01:36.459
they're about hospitals.

00:01:36.459 --> 00:01:39.379
Providers, a doctor in a hospital doing a surgery,

00:01:39.379 --> 00:01:42.860
providing us a care, providing an intervention.

00:01:42.860 --> 00:01:44.059
Well, the world that I live in

00:01:44.059 --> 00:01:45.940
is actually the other side of the coin.

00:01:45.940 --> 00:01:47.900
It's when the patients go home.

00:01:47.900 --> 00:01:50.980
I work with providers all over upstate New York

00:01:50.980 --> 00:01:54.620
that are providing care in the ambulatory setting.

00:01:54.940 --> 00:01:58.580
It's a mix of both primary care and specialist care.

00:01:58.580 --> 00:02:00.699
But the point of it is that all the providers

00:02:00.699 --> 00:02:03.779
that I work with are what we call ambulatory providers,

00:02:03.779 --> 00:02:05.980
which means you can ambulate in,

00:02:05.980 --> 00:02:08.979
you talk to the doctor and you ambulate out.

00:02:08.979 --> 00:02:10.259
This is not inpatient.

00:02:10.259 --> 00:02:13.619
This is not emergency department care.

00:02:13.619 --> 00:02:17.259
This is going in for your annual physical,

00:02:17.259 --> 00:02:19.899
trying to maintain and deal with chronic diseases

00:02:19.899 --> 00:02:22.220
like chronic heart failure, what have you.

00:02:22.259 --> 00:02:26.500
This is not the stuff that we always see on the news

00:02:26.500 --> 00:02:27.339
in the evening.

00:02:27.339 --> 00:02:28.179
You know, you watch your local news,

00:02:28.179 --> 00:02:30.300
it's like, oh, the emergency department

00:02:30.300 --> 00:02:31.419
is reporting this or that.

00:02:31.419 --> 00:02:32.619
That's a little bit different

00:02:32.619 --> 00:02:34.660
than what we're talking about here today.

00:02:35.779 --> 00:02:40.139
All right, so with that, what is Acuitous Health?

00:02:41.699 --> 00:02:43.259
The terminology we like to use

00:02:43.259 --> 00:02:47.020
is that we are a population health services company.

00:02:47.020 --> 00:02:51.500
We help providers make that transition to,

00:02:51.500 --> 00:02:56.139
in America, we are making the transition from a world

00:02:56.139 --> 00:02:57.139
of fee-for-service.

00:02:57.139 --> 00:03:01.139
So you, patient walks in, patient is given some care,

00:03:01.139 --> 00:03:03.660
it is charged, health insurance pays for it.

00:03:03.660 --> 00:03:05.860
The American healthcare system is moving away

00:03:05.860 --> 00:03:07.380
from this fee-for-service model

00:03:07.380 --> 00:03:09.779
into this value-based payment model,

00:03:09.779 --> 00:03:12.660
which is more about trying to codify

00:03:12.660 --> 00:03:16.899
and document the conditions that people are dealing with

00:03:16.899 --> 00:03:19.820
and provide a mechanism to empower providers

00:03:19.820 --> 00:03:23.580
to really treat people holistically

00:03:23.580 --> 00:03:25.539
and to try to make sure that we're actually dealing

00:03:25.539 --> 00:03:28.059
with all of the needs that patients have.

00:03:28.059 --> 00:03:30.820
This is a sea change in how healthcare is provided

00:03:30.820 --> 00:03:33.139
because most medical office models

00:03:33.139 --> 00:03:35.020
are based around the idea of,

00:03:35.020 --> 00:03:37.259
have patients come in, we will do something for them.

00:03:37.259 --> 00:03:39.740
We give them an X-ray, we do whatever.

00:03:39.740 --> 00:03:41.580
The patient walks out, we get paid.

00:03:41.580 --> 00:03:43.979
Value-based payment is a completely different world.

00:03:43.979 --> 00:03:45.220
And so what Acuitous does,

