00:07:12.859 --> 00:07:16.179
So those are sort of our suite of technologies.

00:07:16.179 --> 00:07:18.500
When we started Acuitous, we were very purposeful

00:07:18.500 --> 00:07:22.380
about trying to not have a single technology

00:07:22.380 --> 00:07:26.220
or not have a single language

00:07:26.220 --> 00:07:28.299
that we would try to implement everything in.

00:07:28.299 --> 00:07:30.140
We wanted to recognize that data science

00:07:30.140 --> 00:07:32.820
is a rapidly growing and changing field.

00:07:32.820 --> 00:07:35.540
And that the reality is that we should be trying to use

00:07:35.540 --> 00:07:38.420
the best tool for the job.

00:07:38.420 --> 00:07:41.500
And while people are certainly welcome to argue

00:07:41.500 --> 00:07:44.019
about whether or not we have done that in all instances,

00:07:44.019 --> 00:07:46.579
these were the best choices for us at the time.

00:07:46.579 --> 00:07:48.019
And we have been trying to make sure

00:07:48.019 --> 00:07:50.220
that we are empowering the people on our team.

00:07:50.220 --> 00:07:52.820
Remember I said, it's really about that team.

00:07:52.820 --> 00:07:54.059
So we were trying to make sure

00:07:54.059 --> 00:07:56.140
that we were empowering the people on that team

00:07:56.140 --> 00:07:59.420
to use the technologies that best fit that situation

00:07:59.420 --> 00:08:01.019
and their needs at that moment.

00:08:01.019 --> 00:08:03.420
So that's why we have tried to make sure that we don't do,

00:08:03.540 --> 00:08:05.260
I've worked in other places

00:08:05.260 --> 00:08:07.059
where everything has to be done in SPSS

00:08:07.059 --> 00:08:08.459
or everything has to be done in SAS

00:08:08.459 --> 00:08:10.380
or everything has to be done in R.

00:08:10.380 --> 00:08:12.700
And we have taken the opposite approach

00:08:12.700 --> 00:08:14.420
where we say, let's just try to figure out

00:08:14.420 --> 00:08:18.540
what the best tool for the job is and then use that tool.

00:08:18.540 --> 00:08:21.339
So there's some limits on that.

00:08:21.339 --> 00:08:24.179
I don't think we have anything implemented in Erlang yet,

00:08:24.179 --> 00:08:25.940
but give us time, give us time.

00:08:27.059 --> 00:08:30.339
All right, so some fun facts about Acuitous.

00:08:30.339 --> 00:08:32.260
Acuitous, hence the logo,

00:08:32.260 --> 00:08:35.580
we live in this sometimes uncomfortable space

00:08:35.580 --> 00:08:36.900
between insurance companies,

00:08:36.900 --> 00:08:40.500
AKA payers and your doctor, the provider.

00:08:40.500 --> 00:08:43.539
I tend to use the terminology of payer and provider,

00:08:43.539 --> 00:08:46.780
but when I say payer, I mean medical insurance companies.

00:08:46.780 --> 00:08:48.940
And when I say provider, I mean your doctor

00:08:48.940 --> 00:08:52.140
or the practice sort of more generally.

00:08:52.140 --> 00:08:55.179
It is our job to help both succeed.

00:08:55.179 --> 00:08:58.539
We are currently importing, just for some context

00:08:58.539 --> 00:09:00.059
in terms of what we are dealing with,

00:09:00.099 --> 00:09:04.539
we import EHR data from 14 different vendors.

00:09:04.539 --> 00:09:08.940
And we do so by a variety of means, including ODBC.

00:09:08.940 --> 00:09:13.940
If you are familiar how EHRs are implemented here in the US,

00:09:14.140 --> 00:09:17.059
the Consolidated Clinical Document or CCDA,

00:09:17.059 --> 00:09:19.700
and just good old fashioned CSV.

00:09:19.700 --> 00:09:22.940
We are actually supporting over 200 practices

00:09:22.940 --> 00:09:25.500
in the Capital District and upstate New York region.

00:09:25.500 --> 00:09:28.299
And we work with 11 different payer groups.

00:09:28.299 --> 00:09:30.700
And we do all that as a company

00:09:30.700 --> 00:09:34.099
that is going to turn five next June.

00:09:34.099 --> 00:09:35.739
So we are a very young company.

00:09:35.739 --> 00:09:37.539
We move very fast.

00:09:37.539 --> 00:09:39.739
We break things from time to time,

00:09:39.739 --> 00:09:42.179
but what we are doing is trying to provide

00:09:42.179 --> 00:09:45.340
a highly fluid group of services

00:09:45.340 --> 00:09:47.700
to a very diverse group of providers

00:09:47.700 --> 00:09:49.659
to help them, like I said,

00:09:49.659 --> 00:09:53.299
succeed and thrive in this value-based payment regime.

00:09:53.299 --> 00:09:54.619
And so we live in the middle,

00:09:54.619 --> 00:09:57.880
which is sometimes uncomfortable

00:09:57.880 --> 00:09:59.960
because it's difficult living in the middle

00:09:59.960 --> 00:10:01.760
between two different groups

00:10:01.760 --> 00:10:05.200
that actually have a lot of the same common interest.

00:10:05.200 --> 00:10:06.760
They don't always see themselves

00:10:06.760 --> 00:10:08.400
as having all of the same common interest.

00:10:08.400 --> 00:10:09.760
So we live in the middle,

00:10:09.760 --> 00:10:14.000
helping everyone understand how actually providers

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:16.359
and payers really do have a lot more overlap

00:10:16.359 --> 00:10:19.719
than they have in terms of differences of interest.

00:10:19.719 --> 00:10:22.119
Some context around the provider tools

00:10:22.119 --> 00:10:23.599
that we're going to talk about.

00:10:23.599 --> 00:10:25.799
Let's think about, so I started this saying

00:10:25.799 --> 00:10:29.119
that we were going to connect providers to their data,

00:10:29.119 --> 00:10:30.280
and that is what we do.

00:10:31.359 --> 00:10:34.479
So let's think about what those data sources really are.

00:10:34.479 --> 00:10:37.880
You have EHRs, which are these marvelously complex

00:10:37.880 --> 00:10:40.119
relational data sources

00:10:40.119 --> 00:10:42.679
that have all of the patient history,

00:10:42.679 --> 00:10:44.200
the amount of data that is,

00:10:44.200 --> 00:10:46.400
and by the way, these screenshots,

00:10:46.400 --> 00:10:49.659
no, I pulled these down from the vendor's websites.

00:10:49.659 --> 00:10:51.919
So if there's PHI in this, not my fault.

00:10:53.039 --> 00:10:55.200
These are not screenshots from our clients.

00:10:56.320 --> 00:11:00.320
But an EHR is this incredibly complex thing

00:11:00.320 --> 00:11:02.599
that is, it's basically a filing cabinet

00:11:02.599 --> 00:11:04.799
for everybody's healthcare data.

00:11:04.799 --> 00:11:07.280
And then you have the practice management system,

00:11:07.280 --> 00:11:09.159
which deals with things like billing

00:11:09.159 --> 00:11:11.119
and upcoming appointments, helping, you know,

00:11:11.119 --> 00:11:13.799
you call them up and say, hi, I'd like to see my doctor.

00:11:13.799 --> 00:11:16.080
And they say, okay, so we have an appointment available

00:11:16.080 --> 00:11:18.880
at next Tuesday at two o'clock, can you do that?

00:11:18.880 --> 00:11:21.239
That's what that practice management system is.

00:11:21.239 --> 00:11:24.239
In most practices, these two systems

00:11:24.280 --> 00:11:25.840
live independently of one another.

00:11:25.840 --> 00:11:27.320
They're connected, there's, you know,

00:11:27.320 --> 00:11:29.119
obviously the practice management system

00:11:29.119 --> 00:11:30.840
can tell the EHR there's an appointment,

00:11:30.840 --> 00:11:32.440
so there has to be connectivity.

00:11:33.359 --> 00:11:36.400
Yet at the same time, they are actually separate systems.

00:11:36.400 --> 00:11:39.520
And then other groups of data that exist.

00:11:39.520 --> 00:11:40.520
Here in the United States,

00:11:40.520 --> 00:11:42.840
we have what we call health information exchanges.

00:11:42.840 --> 00:11:45.799
A health information exchange I work with most often

00:11:45.799 --> 00:11:47.280
is called HICSNY.

00:11:47.280 --> 00:11:49.280
And a health information exchange sends out

00:11:49.280 --> 00:11:50.760
what we call an HL7.

00:11:50.760 --> 00:11:54.200
I know so much lingo, I hit healthcare sometimes.

00:11:55.039 --> 00:11:58.359
So an HL7 message is just a fancy way of saying XML.

00:11:58.359 --> 00:12:01.559
And it is an XML message that has some information

00:12:01.559 --> 00:12:03.080
about an event or a patient

00:12:03.080 --> 00:12:05.760
that gets sent out over yield interwebs.

00:12:05.760 --> 00:12:07.359
And so that information goes out

00:12:07.359 --> 00:12:09.080
and usually gets dumped into the EHR

00:12:09.080 --> 00:12:12.520
and notifies the provider of some event or some thing.

00:12:12.520 --> 00:12:14.640
Again, all that's going into the EHR.

00:12:14.640 --> 00:12:16.520
And then of course, the other source of data

00:12:16.520 --> 00:12:19.039
that providers are having to deal with increasingly

00:12:19.039 --> 00:12:20.400
are claims.

00:12:20.400 --> 00:12:23.719
So a patient, you know, the practice management system,

00:12:24.239 --> 00:12:26.559
the EHR know what's going on here.

00:12:26.559 --> 00:12:28.400
But there's this bigger picture of

00:12:28.400 --> 00:12:30.679
when you start trying to talk about a holistic picture

00:12:30.679 --> 00:12:33.159
of what someone is medically,

00:12:33.159 --> 00:12:35.200
there's this larger picture of

00:12:35.200 --> 00:12:38.080
what are other providers doing when there are, you know,

00:12:38.080 --> 00:12:41.440
DAA signed and all this legal stuff gets taken care of.

00:12:41.440 --> 00:12:44.880
How can we leverage the incredible power of claims data,

00:12:44.880 --> 00:12:46.359
the incredible power of these

00:12:46.359 --> 00:12:48.520
health information exchange systems?

00:12:48.520 --> 00:12:51.000
And all of the data providers have historically collected

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:53.359
in their EHR and practice management system.

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:57.119
And the reality is that that big holistic picture

00:12:57.119 --> 00:13:00.599
is what I'm referring today to as population health.

00:13:00.599 --> 00:13:02.440
And there isn't really a stock tool.

00:13:02.440 --> 00:13:05.359
You can't go buy a system for this.

00:13:05.359 --> 00:13:07.799
And in fact, I'm not even sure at this point you can

00:13:07.799 --> 00:13:10.080
because the needs are so regional

00:13:10.080 --> 00:13:12.159
that are so dependent upon what that practice

00:13:12.159 --> 00:13:13.640
is doing at that time.

00:13:13.640 --> 00:13:15.200
Here in the United States,

00:13:15.200 --> 00:13:17.320
the Department of Health and Human Services

00:13:17.320 --> 00:13:19.479
comes out with a new medical model

00:13:19.479 --> 00:13:21.520
roughly every three minutes or so

00:13:21.520 --> 00:13:24.479
that providers may or may not decide to get involved with.

00:13:24.479 --> 00:13:27.760
So the complexity of healthcare

00:13:27.760 --> 00:13:29.320
just within the United States,

00:13:29.320 --> 00:13:30.840
let alone the rest of the world,

00:13:30.840 --> 00:13:32.359
but just within the United States

00:13:32.359 --> 00:13:34.760
is mind bogglingly complex.

00:13:34.760 --> 00:13:38.880
So that's why companies like Aqeulus have been starting up

00:13:38.880 --> 00:13:42.080
is to help support providers in all of this.

00:13:42.080 --> 00:13:44.799
So now, of course, the obvious question is,

00:13:44.799 --> 00:13:47.640
okay, so you say that you're supporting people with this.

00:13:47.640 --> 00:13:49.080
So what does that mean?

00:13:49.080 --> 00:13:50.960
So I'm gonna take you through

00:13:50.960 --> 00:13:53.320
what I'm gonna refer to as some population health tools.

00:13:53.320 --> 00:13:57.000
These are some tools that we have provided for our clients.

00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:00.880
Now, I've already said that this is obviously very tricky

00:14:00.880 --> 00:14:02.479
because there's all these different data sources.

00:14:02.479 --> 00:14:04.760
They don't necessarily wanna talk to one another.

00:14:04.760 --> 00:14:07.320
So effectively, what I've introduced you to

00:14:07.320 --> 00:14:09.960
is the Gordian Knot of modern medicine.

00:14:09.960 --> 00:14:12.599
So we're gonna be a little bit Alexander the Great here,

00:14:12.599 --> 00:14:15.239
and we are going to cut that Gordian Knot,

00:14:15.239 --> 00:14:18.320
and there's only one way that I know of to do this,

00:14:18.320 --> 00:14:20.719
and that's by getting everybody at the table

00:14:21.479 --> 00:14:22.320
and getting them involved.

00:14:22.320 --> 00:14:23.840
So when I show you these tools,

00:14:23.840 --> 00:14:26.000
these are not things that were made

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:28.400
in the back office somewhere,

00:14:28.400 --> 00:14:31.559
and some people, the data science team got together,

00:14:31.559 --> 00:14:33.679
and they're like, oh, this is a cool idea.

00:14:35.799 --> 00:14:37.760
That's not how we do things.

00:14:37.760 --> 00:14:40.599
We are not providing a product like Microsoft

00:14:40.599 --> 00:14:42.599
where we work on it for a couple of years,

00:14:42.599 --> 00:14:44.239
and then shove it out, and we put it in the store,

00:14:44.239 --> 00:14:46.880
and we ask people to buy it.

00:14:46.880 --> 00:14:48.719
We have contracts with providers.

00:14:48.719 --> 00:14:50.440
They need services from us.

00:14:51.280 --> 00:14:54.440
What happens in terms of how we actually get to these tools

00:14:54.440 --> 00:14:57.239
is the providers or the payers come to us and say,

00:14:57.239 --> 00:14:58.840
hey, there's this need.

00:14:58.840 --> 00:15:00.599
We need to be able to communicate around this.

00:15:00.599 --> 00:15:02.080
We need to be able to help people

00:15:02.080 --> 00:15:05.159
navigate this specific space.

00:15:05.159 --> 00:15:07.200
Maybe we need to help with transitions of care.

00:15:07.200 --> 00:15:09.679
So when people leave the inpatient setting,

00:15:09.679 --> 00:15:11.320
how do we make sure that that works?

00:15:11.320 --> 00:15:13.400
How do we make sure that the primary care provider

00:15:13.400 --> 00:15:15.520
is following up with that patient?

00:15:16.400 --> 00:15:18.200
And just if you think about that,

00:15:18.200 --> 00:15:19.919
that transition of care,

00:15:19.919 --> 00:15:22.520
you have a patient leaving the hospital,

00:15:23.640 --> 00:15:25.039
and they're gonna go home.

00:15:25.039 --> 00:15:28.200
And it would be ideal for their primary care provider

00:15:28.200 --> 00:15:30.000
to follow up and provide contact,

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:31.760
you know, check in with them.

00:15:31.760 --> 00:15:33.520
Do we need to talk about your medications?

00:15:33.520 --> 00:15:34.599
How are you feeling?

00:15:34.599 --> 00:15:35.880
Do you need to come in and see me?

00:15:35.880 --> 00:15:38.320
In fact, let me go ahead and schedule that for you.

00:15:38.320 --> 00:15:41.239
That's what we're talking about around transition of care.

00:15:41.239 --> 00:15:42.320
And it's really hard

00:15:42.320 --> 00:15:44.280
because what's happened traditionally

00:15:44.280 --> 00:15:47.640
is EHRs get this message,

00:15:47.640 --> 00:15:49.440
and it gets dumped into the EHR,

00:15:49.440 --> 00:15:52.799
and it may or may not generate an alert for the provider.

00:15:52.799 --> 00:15:54.960
And there's more people at an actual practice

00:15:54.960 --> 00:15:56.320
than just the doctors doing work.

00:15:56.320 --> 00:15:58.320
They have a support team around them.

00:15:58.320 --> 00:16:00.919
So I wanna introduce you to the first tool

00:16:00.919 --> 00:16:03.440
that's going to help us cut this Gordian knot

00:16:03.440 --> 00:16:07.119
is the Health Hospital Activity Monitor, or HAM.

00:16:08.200 --> 00:16:10.159
Now, you will note that the picture

00:16:10.159 --> 00:16:12.599
that I have on the screen at this point

00:16:12.599 --> 00:16:14.200
is of a lump of ham,

00:16:15.039 --> 00:16:15.880
and not the tool,

00:16:15.880 --> 00:16:17.200
which gets us into this really funny thing

00:16:17.200 --> 00:16:19.280
about healthcare is I can't show you

00:16:19.280 --> 00:16:21.320
a lot of what we do directly

00:16:21.320 --> 00:16:24.960
because it's literally chock full of PHI.

00:16:24.960 --> 00:16:28.520
And I don't really want to violate those federal laws,

00:16:28.520 --> 00:16:30.559
so I have to be a little bit careful here.

00:16:30.559 --> 00:16:31.840
I do have some other screenshots,

00:16:31.840 --> 00:16:34.239
but I just wanna acknowledge the pink elephant

00:16:34.239 --> 00:16:36.039
in the room of we're doing things

00:16:36.039 --> 00:16:37.960
that we can't directly show.

00:16:37.960 --> 00:16:41.000
So what is the Hospital Activity Monitor?

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:42.599
HAM, as we call it,

00:16:42.640 --> 00:16:45.479
and you'll see that a lot of our,

00:16:45.479 --> 00:16:46.719
there's a joke with everything.

00:16:46.719 --> 00:16:49.159
We have to have our fun.

00:16:49.159 --> 00:16:52.080
The HAM report is a daily email that goes out.

00:16:52.080 --> 00:16:56.320
It is actually provided to the sites as an Excel file.

00:16:56.320 --> 00:16:58.119
And in that Excel file

00:16:58.119 --> 00:17:00.400
are gonna be a whole bunch of tabs.

00:17:00.400 --> 00:17:01.760
And those tabs have things like,

00:17:01.760 --> 00:17:04.400
here's the list, doctor, you know, whoever.

00:17:04.400 --> 00:17:05.760
Here are the list of your patients

00:17:05.760 --> 00:17:07.560
who, within the last 24 hours,

00:17:07.560 --> 00:17:10.199
were admitted to the hospital.

00:17:10.199 --> 00:17:13.079
So here they are and what the admit reason is.

00:17:13.079 --> 00:17:17.000
These are all patients that have consented

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:20.160
to having their information exchanged over the HIE,

00:17:20.160 --> 00:17:21.719
the Health Information Exchange.

00:17:21.719 --> 00:17:23.199
They have consented to that.

00:17:23.199 --> 00:17:24.520
This doesn't just happen by magic.

00:17:24.520 --> 00:17:25.560
They have to consent.

00:17:26.479 --> 00:17:29.359
If they do consent and they allow their information

00:17:29.359 --> 00:17:32.079
to be sent out over HCME to the provider,

00:17:32.079 --> 00:17:34.439
we pick it up and we give the doctors a report,

00:17:34.439 --> 00:17:36.520
say, hey, these are your patients

00:17:36.520 --> 00:17:40.319
that have been admitted inpatient in the last 24 hours.

00:17:40.319 --> 00:17:41.680
We also have a list of,

00:17:41.680 --> 00:17:43.560
here are the patients who were discharged

00:17:43.560 --> 00:17:45.760
from the hospital in the last 24 hours.

00:17:45.760 --> 00:17:47.400
So they've gone home.

00:17:47.400 --> 00:17:49.000
Somebody should probably follow up with them.

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:50.680
And again, there's context.

00:17:50.680 --> 00:17:51.959
So you can see in terms of, you know,

00:17:51.959 --> 00:17:53.640
what type of stuff we're providing.

00:17:53.640 --> 00:17:54.599
Some of it's really boring.

00:17:54.599 --> 00:17:56.079
The MRN, the name of the date of birth,

00:17:56.079 --> 00:17:58.319
it just helps people know who we're talking about.

00:17:58.319 --> 00:17:59.560
But if you go in and you look at

00:17:59.560 --> 00:18:01.160
some of the event information,

00:18:01.160 --> 00:18:02.520
well, where are they going?

00:18:02.520 --> 00:18:06.359
Where were they admitted to or discharged from?

00:18:07.079 --> 00:18:09.119
So, you know, hospitals that we have up here

00:18:09.119 --> 00:18:11.479
in the Capital District would be places like Albany Med

00:18:11.479 --> 00:18:12.920
or St. Peter's.

00:18:12.920 --> 00:18:16.520
This is, you know, what I mean by an admit facility

00:18:16.520 --> 00:18:18.280
or discharge location.

00:18:18.280 --> 00:18:20.839
Why were they inpatient in the first place?

00:18:20.839 --> 00:18:22.839
What was that primary reason?

00:18:22.839 --> 00:18:24.040
What was the discharge date?

00:18:24.040 --> 00:18:26.800
If there is one, that's obviously only on the discharges.

00:18:26.800 --> 00:18:29.280
And for context, for the provider,

00:18:29.280 --> 00:18:31.719
again, driven by the HIE,

00:18:31.719 --> 00:18:34.119
how many recent ER visits have they had?

00:18:34.119 --> 00:18:36.760
How many recent inpatient visits have they had?

00:18:36.760 --> 00:18:39.400
Because if someone who has an inpatient stay

00:18:39.400 --> 00:18:40.239
and you can look and go,

00:18:40.239 --> 00:18:42.880
wow, in the last year they've had 70 visits

00:18:42.880 --> 00:18:44.280
and now they're inpatient,

00:18:44.280 --> 00:18:45.520
that's a very different patient

00:18:45.520 --> 00:18:48.920
than someone who just went in, you know, overnight.

00:18:48.920 --> 00:18:50.079
You know, we have to try to gauge

00:18:50.079 --> 00:18:53.719
what is the severity of the patient's needs.

00:18:53.719 --> 00:18:57.599
So we try to provide a snapshot picture of what's going on.

00:18:58.560 --> 00:19:00.560
The provider still has the EHR.

00:19:00.560 --> 00:19:01.880
If they have further questions,

00:19:01.880 --> 00:19:06.000
they can go diving through the incredibly rich dataset

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:07.719
that is the EHR.

00:19:07.719 --> 00:19:10.680
This is a snapshot that allows the provider,

00:19:10.680 --> 00:19:13.920
a nurse, a care manager to make rapid decisions

00:19:13.920 --> 00:19:17.119
about which patients really need to be prioritized

00:19:17.119 --> 00:19:19.640
for follow-up upon that transition of care,

00:19:19.640 --> 00:19:21.680
which patients need to be followed up

00:19:21.680 --> 00:19:24.880
while they're actually in the hospital, what have you.

00:19:24.880 --> 00:19:27.040
And all of this thing is about

00:19:27.040 --> 00:19:28.880
really providing patient connectivity

00:19:28.880 --> 00:19:31.959
between the ambulatory primary care provider

00:19:31.959 --> 00:19:34.359
and the patient when they're going in and out of the hospital.

00:19:34.359 --> 00:19:37.199
So that is, well, a whole lot of ham.

00:19:38.560 --> 00:19:40.239
Another tool that we have,

00:19:40.239 --> 00:19:43.800
which we call the Chronic Conditions Report or CCR.

00:19:43.800 --> 00:19:45.400
And this is another Excel file

00:19:45.400 --> 00:19:47.079
that is generated and sent out.

00:19:47.079 --> 00:19:51.000
And both of these, so the, actually back up,

00:19:51.000 --> 00:19:53.680
the Hospital Activity Monitor is actually a Python script

00:19:53.680 --> 00:19:55.760
and the CCR is an R script.

00:19:55.760 --> 00:19:58.520
And these run on what we refer to as our report server,

00:19:58.520 --> 00:20:00.439
which is our Docker powered system

00:20:00.439 --> 00:20:03.160
for emailing out large numbers of Excel files

00:20:03.160 --> 00:20:05.199
that we developed internally.

00:20:05.199 --> 00:20:08.280
The, this is again, an Excel file, like I said,

00:20:08.280 --> 00:20:09.760
and this is something that we send out

00:20:09.760 --> 00:20:12.079
every other week to a site.

00:20:12.079 --> 00:20:14.920
And so if you are familiar with an EHR,

00:20:14.920 --> 00:20:18.479
one of the things that you would know is that EHRs are,

00:20:18.479 --> 00:20:20.719
I kind of compare, oh, you can't see this

00:20:20.719 --> 00:20:21.560
because it's in front of me,

00:20:21.560 --> 00:20:23.680
but I have a filing cabinet in front of me.

00:20:23.680 --> 00:20:25.880
They are a patient filing cabinet.

00:20:25.920 --> 00:20:29.000
All of the information gets put into the right little,

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:31.359
you know, folder inside the EHR for that patient.

00:20:31.359 --> 00:20:35.839
And it's a marvelously rich data source,

00:20:35.839 --> 00:20:40.839
but EHRs are not good at providing the 30,000 foot view

00:20:41.280 --> 00:20:42.239
of what's going on.

00:20:42.239 --> 00:20:44.160
So if you take off in a plane

00:20:44.160 --> 00:20:47.079
and you're flying over, you know, wherever,

00:20:47.079 --> 00:20:50.079
and you look down, you have a completely different view

00:20:50.079 --> 00:20:52.280
of the countryside than you do

00:20:52.280 --> 00:20:54.400
if you are driving down the road.

00:20:54.439 --> 00:20:56.640
And I would say the EHR is like driving down the road

00:20:56.640 --> 00:20:59.000
and using, you know, Google to get you

00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:00.760
from point A to point B.

00:21:00.760 --> 00:21:02.359
And this chronic conditions report,

00:21:02.359 --> 00:21:04.359
this is what you see when you get to the plane,

00:21:04.359 --> 00:21:06.319
because this is full panel data.

00:21:06.319 --> 00:21:09.760
EHRs have, obviously, full panel data.

00:21:09.760 --> 00:21:11.560
And when I say full panel data,

00:21:11.560 --> 00:21:14.199
what I mean is all of the patients at the site.

00:21:14.199 --> 00:21:18.479
So EHRs have that, but when you use an EHR,

00:21:18.479 --> 00:21:21.439
you are looking at just my data or just your data.

00:21:21.439 --> 00:21:24.119
You're not looking at that 30,000 foot view.

00:21:24.800 --> 00:21:27.400
The CCR is that 30,000 foot view.

00:21:27.400 --> 00:21:29.800
So we break it down and we say, okay,

00:21:29.800 --> 00:21:33.719
so how many patients have diabetes at your practice?

00:21:33.719 --> 00:21:36.400
And of those who do, what was their last A1C value?

00:21:37.560 --> 00:21:39.839
Because providers need a way of saying,

00:21:39.839 --> 00:21:41.119
hey, you know, I'd like to be able

00:21:41.119 --> 00:21:42.400
to do this new intervention.

00:21:42.400 --> 00:21:44.199
I've got this new technology

00:21:44.199 --> 00:21:46.959
or I've got this new care manager who's joining my practice.

00:21:46.959 --> 00:21:48.839
And we wanna really be able to target people

00:21:48.839 --> 00:21:51.359
who have an A1C over nine.

00:21:51.359 --> 00:21:53.599
Well, this CCR, what we like to say

00:21:53.599 --> 00:21:55.719
is this democratizes that data

00:21:55.719 --> 00:21:57.719
because without having to come to us

00:21:57.719 --> 00:21:59.359
or to come to anyone else,

00:21:59.359 --> 00:22:01.400
the provider now has the ability to say,

00:22:01.400 --> 00:22:03.599
all right, who are all my patients

00:22:03.599 --> 00:22:06.800
who have diabetes with an A1C over nine?

00:22:06.800 --> 00:22:09.199
They have the ability using this Excel file

00:22:09.199 --> 00:22:11.119
to literally make that list.

00:22:11.119 --> 00:22:13.160
And then they can hand that off to their care manager

00:22:13.160 --> 00:22:14.040
and the office say, please,

00:22:14.040 --> 00:22:16.800
let's go provide some services for these patients.

00:22:16.800 --> 00:22:18.439
It makes it rapid.

00:22:18.439 --> 00:22:20.640
It makes it so that they have full transparency

00:22:20.640 --> 00:22:22.239
into what's going on.

00:22:22.239 --> 00:22:25.239
And you can see the entire list of things

00:22:25.239 --> 00:22:27.439
that we are providing in terms of the types

00:22:27.439 --> 00:22:29.920
of chronic conditions and labs that we target on this.

00:22:29.920 --> 00:22:32.199
And we're adding more slowly.

00:22:32.199 --> 00:22:36.599
It also provides a high level view

00:22:36.599 --> 00:22:38.800
of what are those conditions.

00:22:38.800 --> 00:22:43.400
You can see a risk assessment at this particular provider,

00:22:43.400 --> 00:22:44.719
at this particular 10,

00:22:44.719 --> 00:22:47.199
they do what we call provider risk assessment.

00:22:47.199 --> 00:22:49.800
Provider puts patients into risk levels

00:22:49.839 --> 00:22:53.040
of one, two, three, and four based on clinical criteria.

00:22:53.040 --> 00:22:54.599
Patients who are in level four

00:22:54.599 --> 00:22:57.040
are referred for care management.

00:22:57.040 --> 00:22:58.319
And that CM active is,

00:22:58.319 --> 00:22:59.959
are they active in care management?

00:22:59.959 --> 00:23:00.920
Hicksony consenting.

00:23:00.920 --> 00:23:03.359
So we, you know, can we share their data over Hicksony?

00:23:03.359 --> 00:23:04.760
Do they have diabetes?

00:23:04.760 --> 00:23:05.959
This is how many.

00:23:05.959 --> 00:23:07.680
And an EHR isn't really good at this

00:23:07.680 --> 00:23:09.800
because that's not really what it was designed to do.

00:23:09.800 --> 00:23:11.199
And see, I can finally show a screenshot

00:23:11.199 --> 00:23:12.479
because that says a PHI.

00:23:12.479 --> 00:23:17.040
But this is the kind of data

00:23:17.079 --> 00:23:21.479
that an EHR is not well equipped to provide to a provider.

00:23:23.160 --> 00:23:24.319
The next one here,

00:23:24.319 --> 00:23:26.560
and I've just got one or two more slides here

00:23:26.560 --> 00:23:27.719
before I wrap up,

00:23:27.719 --> 00:23:30.239
but this is what we call our pre-visit planning document.

00:23:30.239 --> 00:23:32.199
So Jane Doe is not a real patient.

00:23:32.199 --> 00:23:33.640
She is not a real person.

00:23:33.640 --> 00:23:36.239
So this is a dummy document,

00:23:36.239 --> 00:23:40.560
but it is emblematic of what our pre-visit planning tool is.

00:23:40.560 --> 00:23:41.880
Again, like I was saying,

00:23:41.880 --> 00:23:43.959
an EHR is super complicated

00:23:43.959 --> 00:23:47.479
and the EHR provides all the detail,

00:23:47.479 --> 00:23:50.719
all of their A1C's values,

00:23:50.719 --> 00:23:52.640
all of their history.

00:23:52.640 --> 00:23:55.839
So we developed this pre-visit planning tool

00:23:55.839 --> 00:23:59.959
to help providers get ready to see you.

00:23:59.959 --> 00:24:02.520
So hopefully in the day or two,

00:24:02.520 --> 00:24:04.680
the week, what have you, before your appointment,

00:24:04.680 --> 00:24:06.280
when you go in to see your provider,

00:24:06.280 --> 00:24:08.239
they sit down and they do a chart review.

00:24:08.239 --> 00:24:10.760
They go through and they think about who you are medically.

00:24:10.760 --> 00:24:12.479
They prepare themselves.

00:24:12.479 --> 00:24:14.839
And because of our role of trying to help providers

00:24:14.839 --> 00:24:17.719
succeed in value-based payment contracts,

00:24:17.719 --> 00:24:20.640
some of the space here is occupied by information

00:24:20.640 --> 00:24:21.800
that will help that provider

00:24:21.800 --> 00:24:23.599
know what things they should be doing.

00:24:23.599 --> 00:24:25.479
So for example, down here,

00:24:25.479 --> 00:24:28.680
we have some lists of cervical cancer screenings

00:24:28.680 --> 00:24:30.040
and this, you know, in that case,

00:24:30.040 --> 00:24:32.319
there's something for them to do.

00:24:32.319 --> 00:24:35.560
But we have a list of things that these are coming,

00:24:35.560 --> 00:24:37.319
these measures are eCQM measures,

00:24:37.319 --> 00:24:38.800
for those of you in the United States.

00:24:38.800 --> 00:24:41.199
These are measures that the doctor should be considering

00:24:41.199 --> 00:24:43.160
about how am I going to fill on this patient?

00:24:43.160 --> 00:24:45.640
This particular patient is apparently very complicated,

00:24:45.640 --> 00:24:49.760
but this is a little over the top in terms of an example,

00:24:49.760 --> 00:24:52.040
but it gives you an idea of what type of information

00:24:52.040 --> 00:24:54.040
is on it, how we're trying to help providers

00:24:54.040 --> 00:24:58.000
identify opportunities to close gaps in care.

00:24:58.000 --> 00:25:00.800
It goes down and has, you know, an ER and inpatient stay.

00:25:00.800 --> 00:25:03.800
So again, we're integrating data from the EHR,

00:25:03.800 --> 00:25:05.040
from HICSNY, from claims.

00:25:05.040 --> 00:25:08.640
All this is getting dumped into this one single document

00:25:08.640 --> 00:25:11.479
that your primary care provider can review

00:25:11.479 --> 00:25:14.560
and try to mentally get ready to provide you

00:25:14.560 --> 00:25:16.079
with the best possible care

00:25:16.079 --> 00:25:18.280
at that point of contact in the office.

00:25:18.280 --> 00:25:20.800
They can sit down and they can see the orders

00:25:20.800 --> 00:25:22.760
and they can say, oh, well, did you follow up on that?

00:25:22.760 --> 00:25:24.439
What have you?

00:25:24.439 --> 00:25:27.119
Then if the provider has further questions,

00:25:27.119 --> 00:25:29.560
again, they still have that EHR.

00:25:29.560 --> 00:25:31.959
They can still go to that and they can open that up

00:25:31.959 --> 00:25:33.119
and go looking through and go, okay,

00:25:33.119 --> 00:25:35.959
so I see that your last A1C was really high.

00:25:35.959 --> 00:25:36.800
What's a 12?

00:25:36.800 --> 00:25:38.800
That's not good.

00:25:38.800 --> 00:25:42.760
But they can go into the EHR and say, okay, you had 112.

00:25:42.760 --> 00:25:45.239
Everything else was pretty good and you had 112.

00:25:45.239 --> 00:25:48.880
That's different than a patient that's got lots of 12s.

00:25:49.880 --> 00:25:51.680
12 is a not good A1C.

00:25:51.680 --> 00:25:54.719
So they still may have to go to the EHR

00:25:54.719 --> 00:25:56.839
to really kind of put that full picture together,

00:25:56.839 --> 00:26:00.040
but we're providing a snapshot of information

00:26:00.040 --> 00:26:01.439
that really helps the provider

00:26:01.439 --> 00:26:03.319
get their head in the right space

00:26:03.319 --> 00:26:05.599
so that when they walk in to see you,

00:26:05.599 --> 00:26:07.520
they are ready, they know what's going on,

00:26:07.520 --> 00:26:10.959
and they have some context for where you are medically.

00:26:10.959 --> 00:26:13.199
The last tool I've got I wanted to talk about

00:26:13.199 --> 00:26:16.680
just because this is an R in epidemiology thing.

00:26:16.680 --> 00:26:18.439
Kind of seems like we need a Shiny application

00:26:18.439 --> 00:26:20.199
shown off somewhere in this thing.

00:26:20.199 --> 00:26:23.520
So this is a Shiny app that we made,

00:26:23.520 --> 00:26:26.000
and it's also, I wanted to use this as an opportunity

00:26:26.000 --> 00:26:28.319
to highlight something that's not EHR-driven.

00:26:28.319 --> 00:26:29.479
A lot of our tools are,

00:26:29.479 --> 00:26:31.760
because we are connecting providers to their data,

00:26:31.760 --> 00:26:32.800
EHR-driven.

00:26:32.800 --> 00:26:34.719
Of course they are.

00:26:34.719 --> 00:26:37.400
This appointment trends application is not.

00:26:37.400 --> 00:26:40.560
In fact, there is almost no EHR data

00:26:40.560 --> 00:26:41.920
in this thing whatsoever.

00:26:41.920 --> 00:26:44.400
Also fun, because that means I can do screenshots.

00:26:44.400 --> 00:26:47.959
But what this is really being driven by

00:26:47.959 --> 00:26:50.239
is by that practice management tool.

00:26:50.239 --> 00:26:51.640
You've got appointments coming up.

00:26:51.640 --> 00:26:54.239
You've got appointments showing up or not.

00:26:54.239 --> 00:26:55.959
If you would all recall,

00:26:58.239 --> 00:27:00.079
back in March of 2020,

00:27:00.079 --> 00:27:02.839
the state of New York shut itself down.

00:27:03.800 --> 00:27:07.239
So what this tool came about was over about a weekend

00:27:07.239 --> 00:27:08.719
after COVID-19 hit,

00:27:08.719 --> 00:27:11.000
and New York City and the New York State

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:13.479
just a day or two later started shutting down.

00:27:13.479 --> 00:27:16.400
Providers started calling us and saying,

00:27:16.400 --> 00:27:18.719
I know that people are not going to show up

00:27:18.719 --> 00:27:20.439
for their appointments.

00:27:20.439 --> 00:27:21.479
Sorry, I didn't mean to do that.

00:27:21.479 --> 00:27:23.439
I know patients aren't going to show up

00:27:23.439 --> 00:27:24.359
for their appointments.

00:27:24.359 --> 00:27:26.560
I know that my numbers are decreasing of appointments,

00:27:26.560 --> 00:27:27.800
but I don't have a limitability

00:27:27.800 --> 00:27:29.479
to wrap my head around what that means.

00:27:29.479 --> 00:27:31.160
I don't know how bad.

00:27:31.199 --> 00:27:35.959
We were able to very rapidly put together a tool.

00:27:35.959 --> 00:27:37.680
It started off as a flex dashboard

00:27:37.680 --> 00:27:38.719
that we emailed the people,

00:27:38.719 --> 00:27:40.839
and later we were able to put it together

00:27:40.839 --> 00:27:42.000
as a shiny application

00:27:42.000 --> 00:27:45.520
that now lives actually in our network.

00:27:45.520 --> 00:27:48.000
And that purple line is 2020.

00:27:48.000 --> 00:27:51.239
And you can see the fall off the crater there

00:27:51.239 --> 00:27:53.479
is right there as we go into March of 2020

00:27:53.479 --> 00:27:56.800
when COVID-19 causes New York State to shut down hard

00:27:56.800 --> 00:27:58.800
to deal with the epidemic.

00:27:58.800 --> 00:28:00.160
And the green line up there

00:28:00.160 --> 00:28:02.319
is what it should look like from 2019.

00:28:02.319 --> 00:28:04.319
So a little bit of a difference.

00:28:04.319 --> 00:28:08.400
This tool also was able to be adapted

00:28:08.400 --> 00:28:10.000
to help providers understand,

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:12.479
okay, I know my in-person numbers are crashing.

00:28:12.479 --> 00:28:14.079
That's what that screenshot is.

00:28:14.079 --> 00:28:16.880
But they were also implementing remote care.

00:28:16.880 --> 00:28:19.959
All of a sudden, kind of wild,

00:28:19.959 --> 00:28:22.760
you could go to your doctor on Zoom

00:28:22.760 --> 00:28:24.680
and have an entire medical visit

00:28:24.680 --> 00:28:26.680
where you didn't even have to be in the same room

00:28:26.680 --> 00:28:27.760
with your provider.

00:28:27.760 --> 00:28:30.199
And all of a sudden, we shoved medicine

00:28:30.199 --> 00:28:31.839
into the 21st century.

00:28:31.839 --> 00:28:34.359
And the practice sites were working really hard

00:28:34.359 --> 00:28:35.680
to implement these technologies,

00:28:35.680 --> 00:28:37.839
and they were honestly doing a really good job.

00:28:37.839 --> 00:28:40.959
What they didn't know was were they plugging the hole?

00:28:40.959 --> 00:28:45.160
They said, I know my in-person numbers are down.

00:28:45.160 --> 00:28:48.400
Am I plugging that hole with these remote visits?

00:28:48.400 --> 00:28:50.280
And so this tool actually has the ability

00:28:50.280 --> 00:28:51.439
to let us go in and track.

00:28:51.439 --> 00:28:52.719
And of course, it varies by the site,

00:28:52.719 --> 00:28:54.880
and it varies by the type of care provided.

00:28:54.880 --> 00:28:57.800
But we were able to start helping providers understand,

00:28:57.800 --> 00:29:01.359
yes, your in-person visits are way, way down.

00:29:01.359 --> 00:29:03.839
This is to the extent that you're able to make that up

00:29:03.839 --> 00:29:07.199
using remote technologies, remote visits, et cetera,

00:29:07.199 --> 00:29:09.160
doing phone calls, what have you,

00:29:09.160 --> 00:29:10.719
to really try to make up that hole,

00:29:10.719 --> 00:29:12.760
make up that gap, plug that hole.

00:29:12.760 --> 00:29:15.239
This was a tool that came about,

00:29:15.239 --> 00:29:17.400
I wanna say the initial version of this,

00:29:17.400 --> 00:29:19.800
we put together literally in one weekend.

00:29:19.800 --> 00:29:21.239
And we were able to get this out.

00:29:21.239 --> 00:29:22.079
And by the end of the year,

00:29:22.119 --> 00:29:25.760
it is now a standing application

00:29:25.760 --> 00:29:28.959
that some of our practice sites continue to use

00:29:28.959 --> 00:29:32.800
here in 2021 to understand what their numbers

00:29:32.800 --> 00:29:34.880
are looking like trending over time,

00:29:34.880 --> 00:29:39.000
because simply put, appointments mean revenue.

00:29:39.000 --> 00:29:41.719
So while one blip depends,

00:29:41.719 --> 00:29:44.319
how much revenue depends on what the appointment is,

00:29:44.319 --> 00:29:45.520
your appointments are going up,

00:29:45.520 --> 00:29:48.520
revenue will eventually follow.

00:29:48.560 --> 00:29:52.119
So just one more application that we were able to do

00:29:52.119 --> 00:29:54.520
to help them see that 30,000 foot view

00:29:54.520 --> 00:29:56.280
of what their practice looked like.

00:29:57.319 --> 00:30:01.640
All right, so that was my presentation.

