00:32:16.239 --> 00:32:18.880
The next one, Andy, is about large data.

00:32:18.880 --> 00:32:20.880
How do you deal with large data sets

00:32:20.880 --> 00:32:23.160
greater than a hundred gigabytes using R?

00:32:23.160 --> 00:32:25.079
I tend to use SAS to do data wrangling

00:32:25.079 --> 00:32:26.959
since R is limited by RAM size.

00:32:26.959 --> 00:32:28.959
Is there a way to solve this in R?

00:32:30.079 --> 00:32:32.439
So I guess the first question

00:32:32.439 --> 00:32:36.079
that I would address with that is,

00:32:37.040 --> 00:32:38.800
so if you have very, very large data,

00:32:38.800 --> 00:32:41.359
a hundred gigabytes is pretty big.

00:32:42.280 --> 00:32:44.680
What are you trying to do with that?

00:32:44.680 --> 00:32:47.520
So the solution that I would suggest

00:32:47.520 --> 00:32:50.319
if you are doing some kind of a machine learning model

00:32:50.319 --> 00:32:53.079
would be different than if you are trying

00:32:53.079 --> 00:32:55.839
to do some sort of summarization.

00:32:55.839 --> 00:32:59.719
Because if what you are trying to do is say,

00:32:59.719 --> 00:33:01.880
so practice management data is something

00:33:01.880 --> 00:33:04.520
that tends to scale up into the OMG scale

00:33:04.520 --> 00:33:06.560
because just think about how many appointments

00:33:06.560 --> 00:33:08.839
a provider has in a day.

00:33:10.040 --> 00:33:11.680
I'm talking to a provider like one doctor

00:33:11.680 --> 00:33:13.880
and there's often more than one doctor at a site

00:33:13.880 --> 00:33:15.760
and we're working with over 200 sites.

00:33:15.760 --> 00:33:19.800
So our practice management data is large, it's deep.

00:33:20.880 --> 00:33:23.959
I don't usually need to do a machine learning model

00:33:23.959 --> 00:33:27.199
off of the full cohort of that data.

00:33:27.199 --> 00:33:29.439
So what we actually do and what I would recommend

00:33:29.439 --> 00:33:32.839
if this is a relevant opportunity for you

00:33:32.880 --> 00:33:34.800
is to use a database server.

00:33:34.800 --> 00:33:37.439
Because yes, R is memory bound.

00:33:37.439 --> 00:33:40.560
And, but if what I really need, for example,

00:33:40.560 --> 00:33:43.560
going back to this, our appointment trend

00:33:43.560 --> 00:33:45.040
is going up or down.

00:33:45.040 --> 00:33:48.560
That calculation of how many appointments

00:33:48.560 --> 00:33:50.520
are happening in a day,

00:33:50.520 --> 00:33:53.119
that is not actually being calculated in R.

00:33:53.119 --> 00:33:55.800
I'm actually offloading that through dbplyr

00:33:55.800 --> 00:33:58.520
onto the database server and it's calculating

00:33:58.520 --> 00:34:00.560
the number of appointments per day.

00:34:00.599 --> 00:34:02.839
R is only in this, in the instance

00:34:02.839 --> 00:34:05.239
of this particular application,

00:34:05.239 --> 00:34:08.919
it's having to graph a number of, you know, about 50K.

00:34:08.919 --> 00:34:11.679
It's an integer and this is the monthly view.

00:34:11.679 --> 00:34:14.040
So there's only, you know, there's two lines,

00:34:14.040 --> 00:34:15.280
there's only 12 months in a year.

00:34:15.280 --> 00:34:18.239
So at most 24, 48, you know, data points.

00:34:18.239 --> 00:34:23.080
So hundreds and hundreds of thousands of appointments,

00:34:23.080 --> 00:34:27.320
but I can slim it down to 48 data points

00:34:27.360 --> 00:34:31.840
and R is really, you can graph that on a pocket calculator.

00:34:31.840 --> 00:34:34.479
So if you can use a database server,

00:34:34.479 --> 00:34:35.639
I would recommend that.

00:34:35.639 --> 00:34:40.639
If you can't, there are using virtual machines.

00:34:40.840 --> 00:34:42.560
Other jobs that I've done where I needed

00:34:42.560 --> 00:34:44.439
to do machine learning models on very,

00:34:44.439 --> 00:34:47.080
very large data sets, I used virtual machines

00:34:47.080 --> 00:34:49.879
where I could actually have an arbitrary amount of RAM,

00:34:49.879 --> 00:34:52.479
but there you have to have the budget to pay for it.

00:34:53.479 --> 00:34:55.280
Thanks, Andy.

