00:36:07.000 --> 00:36:08.919
were here to help me with this.

00:36:08.919 --> 00:36:10.560
But the very first step is what we have,

00:36:10.560 --> 00:36:12.439
what you would have to do is get a DAA.

00:36:12.439 --> 00:36:14.840
You actually have to get permission to access that data.

00:36:14.840 --> 00:36:18.959
So obviously in America, we have what we call PHI laws,

00:36:19.000 --> 00:36:21.639
which very tightly control

00:36:21.639 --> 00:36:25.000
who can have access to private health data.

00:36:25.000 --> 00:36:26.760
And those laws are very important.

00:36:26.760 --> 00:36:27.840
And if you violate them,

00:36:27.840 --> 00:36:29.479
there are very significant consequences.

00:36:29.479 --> 00:36:31.840
May I suggest you do not violate those?

00:36:31.840 --> 00:36:35.800
So the very first step is to get a DAA with the practice.

00:36:35.800 --> 00:36:38.320
And then once we have that DAA with the practice

00:36:38.320 --> 00:36:41.760
and the doctor has to say, Acuitous Health,

00:36:41.760 --> 00:36:46.199
I am licensing Acuitous Health to be a third party vendor

00:36:46.199 --> 00:36:49.280
and they're going to work with me to manage my EHR data.

00:36:49.280 --> 00:36:51.239
Then we reach out to their vendor,

00:36:52.560 --> 00:36:55.360
Allscripts, Cerner, whoever.

00:36:55.360 --> 00:36:56.959
And we start working with them

00:36:56.959 --> 00:37:01.479
and the details here kind of depend on who the vendor is

00:37:01.479 --> 00:37:04.040
and how that particular site has that tool set up.

00:37:04.040 --> 00:37:07.120
And we start working with them on an information exchange

00:37:07.120 --> 00:37:09.040
so that we can access that data.

00:37:09.040 --> 00:37:10.719
So that's where we started getting into,

00:37:10.719 --> 00:37:12.199
it might be an ODBC connection,

00:37:12.199 --> 00:37:14.719
it might be a flat file, what have you.

00:37:14.719 --> 00:37:16.560
And then we are able to pull that down.

00:37:16.560 --> 00:37:19.320
Our data is, it is in the cloud,

00:37:19.320 --> 00:37:21.959
but it's in a PHI grade,

00:37:21.959 --> 00:37:24.399
the expensive grade of all VMs,

00:37:24.399 --> 00:37:27.280
because no, we can't just let people access that data

00:37:27.280 --> 00:37:28.760
because obviously it's private.

00:37:28.760 --> 00:37:31.719
We have information that people have the right

00:37:31.719 --> 00:37:34.120
to have privately and keep private.

00:37:34.120 --> 00:37:36.120
So that is data that,

00:37:36.120 --> 00:37:38.399
hence why I had to be sort of careful and make

00:37:39.600 --> 00:37:44.199
silly CCR jokes and ham jokes throughout this presentation,

00:37:44.199 --> 00:37:46.959
because the actual spreadsheet

00:37:46.959 --> 00:37:50.560
of the hospital activity monitor, I didn't want,

00:37:50.560 --> 00:37:53.439
if I had put it up here, it would have been two thirds,

00:37:53.439 --> 00:37:55.600
obfuscated out, I would have had to have like

00:37:55.600 --> 00:37:57.760
made it really hard to read

00:37:57.760 --> 00:37:59.840
so it wouldn't have been much fun to look at.

00:37:59.840 --> 00:38:01.679
So I felt like it was better to approach this,

00:38:01.679 --> 00:38:04.040
but no, we have to be very careful around healthcare

00:38:04.040 --> 00:38:06.320
and data exchange within this world,

00:38:07.199 --> 00:38:10.719
which is good, but it also makes everything complicated.

00:38:10.719 --> 00:38:12.080
Did I answer your question?

00:38:15.199 --> 00:38:16.040
Yes, you did.

00:38:16.040 --> 00:38:17.479
Thank you so much, Andy.

00:38:17.479 --> 00:38:18.800
I hope I wasn't rambling.

00:38:18.800 --> 00:38:19.639
I wasn't mute.

00:38:20.719 --> 00:38:21.560
Thanks, Andy.

00:38:22.439 --> 00:38:24.639
Jocelyn, I see you had just asked a question

00:38:24.639 --> 00:38:28.040
in the Zoom chat and I wanted to pass the mic over to you

00:38:28.040 --> 00:38:29.679
if that's okay to ask that live.

00:38:31.080 --> 00:38:32.679
Yes, thanks, Rachel.

00:38:32.679 --> 00:38:34.679
So my question is how do you track

00:38:34.679 --> 00:38:38.280
a patient's medical history when you look at their

00:38:39.800 --> 00:38:41.280
service chart?

00:38:41.719 --> 00:38:43.320
Because during the years,

00:38:43.320 --> 00:38:45.239
a patient could change their plans

00:38:45.239 --> 00:38:48.280
and have multiple patient ID or insurance plans ID.

00:38:48.280 --> 00:38:50.919
So how do you track their medical history?

00:38:51.919 --> 00:38:54.320
That is a really good question, actually.

00:38:54.320 --> 00:38:56.719
So inside our platform,

00:38:56.719 --> 00:38:59.600
we actually use an MDM tool called MultiView.

00:38:59.600 --> 00:39:00.959
And what MultiView does,

00:39:00.959 --> 00:39:04.879
and no tool of this nature is perfect.

00:39:04.879 --> 00:39:06.919
We have tuned ours to a place

00:39:06.919 --> 00:39:08.320
that we're very comfortable with,

00:39:08.320 --> 00:39:09.679
but is it perfect?

00:39:09.679 --> 00:39:10.520
Nope.

00:39:10.520 --> 00:39:11.360
Will it ever be?

00:39:12.600 --> 00:39:13.639
Nope.

00:39:13.639 --> 00:39:16.040
But what this does is it allows us to connect.

00:39:16.040 --> 00:39:18.719
So I mentioned that we work with, I believe,

00:39:18.719 --> 00:39:20.840
we work with 11 different payer groups,

00:39:20.840 --> 00:39:23.639
multiple different provider groups.

00:39:23.639 --> 00:39:26.679
And so you mentioned the complexity of,

00:39:26.679 --> 00:39:31.679
I went from Blue Shield to CDPHP insurance.

00:39:32.439 --> 00:39:34.919
For example, at some point in the past,

00:39:34.919 --> 00:39:36.360
I used to have Blue Shield.

00:39:36.360 --> 00:39:37.760
Right now I have CDPHP.

00:39:37.800 --> 00:39:38.959
I used to have Blue Shield.

00:39:38.959 --> 00:39:40.879
Right now I have CDPHP insurance.

00:39:40.879 --> 00:39:42.800
So I have a new provider.

00:39:42.800 --> 00:39:45.679
I have a new payer ID on that.

00:39:45.679 --> 00:39:48.439
Some number with Blue Shield,

00:39:48.439 --> 00:39:50.439
that was a record number with them.

00:39:50.439 --> 00:39:52.199
And I have a new record number with CDPHP,

00:39:52.199 --> 00:39:53.439
which is obviously not the same.

00:39:53.439 --> 00:39:55.280
And yes, we, up to a point,

00:39:55.280 --> 00:39:57.199
are able to track people across those

00:39:57.199 --> 00:39:59.479
because we use this MultiView

00:39:59.479 --> 00:40:01.679
that'll go in and look at first name, last name,

00:40:01.679 --> 00:40:03.280
date of birth, gender,

00:40:03.280 --> 00:40:05.439
and a whole bunch of other criteria

00:40:05.439 --> 00:40:09.919
to try to guess that Andy in this data set

00:40:09.919 --> 00:40:12.399
is the same Andy as in this data set.

00:40:13.439 --> 00:40:15.879
We also have to be very careful about that

00:40:15.879 --> 00:40:19.360
because there are very complex rules

00:40:19.360 --> 00:40:22.280
around when we can combine that data and share it

00:40:22.280 --> 00:40:23.320
and when we can't.

00:40:23.320 --> 00:40:25.120
Again, because we have to be very conscientious

00:40:25.120 --> 00:40:26.320
around privacy.

00:40:26.320 --> 00:40:28.840
So anytime we start doing things that,

00:40:28.840 --> 00:40:32.600
any process that starts to walk across multiple data sets,

00:40:32.600 --> 00:40:34.199
we have to stop, take a deep breath,

00:40:34.199 --> 00:40:36.280
and really, really, really think it through

00:40:36.280 --> 00:40:37.879
from a legal and privacy standpoint

00:40:37.879 --> 00:40:40.399
to make sure that we're not doing something inappropriate.

00:40:40.399 --> 00:40:43.639
But yeah, we use a tool called MultiView to help us say,

00:40:44.600 --> 00:40:46.360
the other part that can be fun,

00:40:46.360 --> 00:40:49.320
that can be complicated,

00:40:49.320 --> 00:40:52.120
is you as an individual patient

00:40:52.120 --> 00:40:53.239
over the course of your life

00:40:53.239 --> 00:40:55.439
will have multiple providers.

00:40:55.439 --> 00:40:57.280
Just imagine as a simple example,

00:40:57.280 --> 00:40:59.719
a kid who goes from having a pediatrician

00:40:59.719 --> 00:41:02.120
to eventually a family medicine practitioner.

00:41:02.120 --> 00:41:05.560
And that could be in multiple EHRs.

00:41:05.560 --> 00:41:06.879
So we're also able to,

00:41:06.879 --> 00:41:09.439
on behalf of the payer groups that we work with,

00:41:09.439 --> 00:41:13.840
map that progression across different EHR systems

00:41:13.840 --> 00:41:14.679
so that we can say,

00:41:14.679 --> 00:41:16.600
hey, this is how that particular healthcare

00:41:16.600 --> 00:41:19.040
for this patient who has had your insurance

00:41:19.040 --> 00:41:21.040
for all those years has been developing.

00:41:21.959 --> 00:41:24.239
But again, that's something that both has both technical

00:41:24.239 --> 00:41:27.239
and legal and privacy aspects to it.

00:41:28.239 --> 00:41:29.239
Thank you very much.

00:41:31.239 --> 00:41:32.080
Awesome.

