00:41:33.679 --> 00:41:35.800
or I'm sorry, the Slido for the next one.

00:41:36.879 --> 00:41:39.040
I'm gonna ask one that I'm particularly interested

00:41:39.040 --> 00:41:40.800
in the answer of, Andy,

00:41:40.800 --> 00:41:43.120
and it's, are there other quick tools

00:41:43.120 --> 00:41:44.439
you've had to make in Shiny

00:41:44.439 --> 00:41:46.719
like the Appointment Trends app?

00:41:47.600 --> 00:41:49.800
Oh, gosh, yes.

00:41:49.800 --> 00:41:54.800
We generate Shiny apps weekly.

00:41:55.520 --> 00:41:56.360
Weekly?

00:41:57.280 --> 00:42:00.199
So things that we are doing in Shiny right now,

00:42:01.080 --> 00:42:02.439
on a technical side.

00:42:02.439 --> 00:42:05.320
So I mentioned that we use that Health Catalyst platform

00:42:05.320 --> 00:42:06.560
and they have a number of tools

00:42:06.560 --> 00:42:09.080
that go through and do that ETL and all those jobs.

00:42:09.080 --> 00:42:10.399
We actually have been starting

00:42:10.399 --> 00:42:12.479
to develop our own Shiny applications

00:42:12.479 --> 00:42:14.919
to help us manage the data warehouse

00:42:14.919 --> 00:42:17.760
so that we can have better insight into what's running,

00:42:17.760 --> 00:42:19.679
how long do those things run?

00:42:19.679 --> 00:42:22.399
We have a series of Shiny dashboards that we built

00:42:22.399 --> 00:42:24.879
that go beyond what the Health Catalyst platform

00:42:24.879 --> 00:42:28.840
provides out of the box to help us meet our needs.

00:42:28.840 --> 00:42:30.879
Related to that, not actually Shiny,

00:42:30.879 --> 00:42:32.399
but it's kind of fun internally.

00:42:32.399 --> 00:42:36.600
We also use Slack probably too much.

00:42:36.600 --> 00:42:39.879
And so if you happen to work someplace that use Slack,

00:42:39.879 --> 00:42:41.760
you understand the emoji hell

00:42:41.760 --> 00:42:44.040
that we've all been living in in the last 18 months.

00:42:44.040 --> 00:42:47.479
But the other thing that we do

00:42:47.479 --> 00:42:49.639
is that we have our markdown reports.

00:42:49.639 --> 00:42:52.320
And for example, some of those are about our ETL jobs.

00:42:53.120 --> 00:42:56.120
We actually have channels for our dev and prod environments.

00:42:56.120 --> 00:42:59.679
And one of the members of our team

00:42:59.679 --> 00:43:01.239
who's absolutely phenomenal,

00:43:01.239 --> 00:43:04.760
she wrote an R Markdown script that runs every morning

00:43:04.760 --> 00:43:06.159
and it puts out a list of,

00:43:06.159 --> 00:43:08.040
these are your jobs that failed last night.

00:43:08.040 --> 00:43:09.639
You need a human to go look at them.

00:43:09.639 --> 00:43:11.560
And that is something that gets then dumped into,

00:43:11.560 --> 00:43:13.439
nobody actually looks at it on,

00:43:13.439 --> 00:43:16.320
the R Markdown generator is actually ignored.

00:43:16.320 --> 00:43:18.479
What we use is the side effect of it

00:43:18.479 --> 00:43:20.000
that gets shoved into Slack.

00:43:20.000 --> 00:43:21.239
And we're able to read that.

00:43:21.239 --> 00:43:23.199
It's in our communications platform

00:43:23.199 --> 00:43:26.239
and it's from an R script that's running on RStudio Connect,

00:43:26.239 --> 00:43:27.479
but it gets dumped into Slack,

00:43:27.479 --> 00:43:29.560
which is where we live moment to moment.

00:43:29.560 --> 00:43:31.800
And it says, hey, these ETL jobs failed

00:43:31.800 --> 00:43:34.000
and a human needs to go figure out why and fix it.

00:43:34.000 --> 00:43:39.000
And every morning, what we call the IO team looks at that

00:43:39.080 --> 00:43:43.120
and starts figuring out how to make our ETL spend better.

00:43:44.120 --> 00:43:45.760
And then in terms of the providers,

00:43:45.760 --> 00:43:49.159
we have a number and I couldn't go through them all in part.

00:43:50.040 --> 00:43:51.840
I was told to keep it to about half an hour.

00:43:51.840 --> 00:43:55.479
And we have so many shiny apps.

00:43:55.479 --> 00:43:56.879
We have things that are helping people

00:43:56.879 --> 00:43:58.879
with financial analytics.

00:43:58.879 --> 00:44:03.280
We have things that are helping folks with care management.

00:44:03.280 --> 00:44:04.879
We have a whole bunch of different things

00:44:04.879 --> 00:44:06.879
that we have been doing that kind of try to walk

00:44:06.879 --> 00:44:09.800
that gamut of data sources that we deal with.

00:44:09.800 --> 00:44:14.280
So yeah, shiny is a very important part of what we do

00:44:14.280 --> 00:44:16.320
as our static R Markdown files.

00:44:16.600 --> 00:44:17.439
That's amazing.

