01:01:44.199 --> 01:01:45.959
and sort of like an iterative loop

01:01:45.959 --> 01:01:49.159
where the physician who sees this patient will know

01:01:49.159 --> 01:01:51.840
or have an action item to get the blood panel

01:01:51.840 --> 01:01:55.600
to best predict whether readmission is highly likely

01:01:55.600 --> 01:01:58.080
for a patient at a later date?

01:01:58.080 --> 01:02:00.000
You know, is there a feedback loop sort of

01:02:00.000 --> 01:02:03.000
to make sure patient outcomes improve?

01:02:03.000 --> 01:02:05.879
Yeah, that is something that we could implement.

01:02:05.879 --> 01:02:10.879
That would most likely already be driven,

01:02:12.080 --> 01:02:15.479
unless we came up with some sort of a novel lab,

01:02:15.479 --> 01:02:18.080
you know, correlation, that's probably already

01:02:18.080 --> 01:02:21.040
going to be driven natively by the EHR,

01:02:21.040 --> 01:02:24.239
in which case we would just offload that to the EHR

01:02:24.239 --> 01:02:26.120
to drive, you know, getting that lab completion

01:02:26.120 --> 01:02:28.719
and all of that, getting those results into the EHR.

01:02:31.520 --> 01:02:34.879
But no, I mean, what you're saying absolutely makes sense.

01:02:34.879 --> 01:02:37.080
One of the things, you used a word

01:02:37.080 --> 01:02:40.120
that is worth highlighting, which is feedback loop.

01:02:40.120 --> 01:02:42.639
And one of the things that we are very conscientious

01:02:42.639 --> 01:02:46.239
about doing anytime, if it's a tool or a model

01:02:46.239 --> 01:02:49.600
or anything else, is involving the provider.

01:02:49.600 --> 01:02:53.840
So not only would they, you know, a provider ask us

01:02:53.840 --> 01:02:57.439
for some sort of a model or something like readmission risk,

01:02:57.439 --> 01:02:59.879
but we would also have those people involved

01:02:59.879 --> 01:03:01.639
in the development of the model,

01:03:01.639 --> 01:03:04.560
because what we have found is not only

01:03:05.239 --> 01:03:06.800
does that increase the trust in the model,

01:03:06.800 --> 01:03:09.320
it also gets people to really start using it,

01:03:09.320 --> 01:03:11.600
because anytime you have a model, it's a model,

01:03:11.600 --> 01:03:13.760
it's not reality, it's not perfect.

01:03:13.760 --> 01:03:18.000
And having those providers involved from the very beginning,

01:03:18.000 --> 01:03:19.600
in terms of that feedback loop of talking

01:03:19.600 --> 01:03:22.479
about what this model is, helps them get the understanding

01:03:22.479 --> 01:03:23.879
of, well, when is the model right?

01:03:23.879 --> 01:03:25.800
When is the model likely a little bit off?

01:03:25.800 --> 01:03:28.280
You know, what are the weaknesses of that model?

01:03:28.280 --> 01:03:31.840
So having a feedback loop on any data science project

01:03:31.840 --> 01:03:34.040
back and forth between those domain experts

01:03:34.520 --> 01:03:36.239
and the people doing, you know, the data science

01:03:36.239 --> 01:03:38.560
and the technical side is critical.

01:03:42.040 --> 01:03:42.879
Thanks, Andy.

01:03:42.879 --> 01:03:45.040
I know we're about 10 minutes over,

01:03:45.040 --> 01:03:47.600
so I just want to be respectful of your time,

01:03:47.600 --> 01:03:50.800
especially if you have to run to another meeting too.

01:03:50.800 --> 01:03:53.520
Yeah, I do have a one that I need to get to here

01:03:53.520 --> 01:03:55.000
at some point.

01:03:55.000 --> 01:03:58.520
Okay, so thank you so much.

01:03:58.520 --> 01:04:01.360
I know there's a few other unanswered questions,

01:04:01.360 --> 01:04:04.639
is it okay if we just ask you one last one,

01:04:04.639 --> 01:04:07.280
which was, I see this one, I've been upvoted.

01:04:07.280 --> 01:04:10.600
How do you suggest our users normalize our use

01:04:10.600 --> 01:04:13.719
when so many people are using SAS or SPSS?

01:04:17.800 --> 01:04:18.919
Fun question.

01:04:18.919 --> 01:04:21.399
I have been accused of doing this.

01:04:21.399 --> 01:04:24.199
Our advocacy is something I have been accused of before.

01:04:25.439 --> 01:04:28.120
So what I would actually say is,

01:04:28.120 --> 01:04:29.520
so previously I worked

01:04:29.560 --> 01:04:31.560
at the New York State Department of Health,

01:04:31.560 --> 01:04:33.679
and we had an organization within that,

01:04:33.679 --> 01:04:35.439
it was called EBCOP,

01:04:35.439 --> 01:04:38.080
which was Epidemiology and Biostatistics Community

01:04:38.080 --> 01:04:39.879
of Practice, you know,

01:04:39.879 --> 01:04:42.600
because there needed to be another acronym in healthcare.

01:04:42.600 --> 01:04:45.439
And within the bounds of EBCOP,

01:04:45.439 --> 01:04:47.959
what I was able to start doing was starting a conversation

01:04:47.959 --> 01:04:50.919
around both R and ultimately also aversion control,

01:04:50.919 --> 01:04:55.159
but trying to like start talking about how it could be used,

01:04:55.159 --> 01:04:57.800
ultimately having a new,

01:04:58.080 --> 01:05:00.719
a language that's a little bit different than say SAS,

01:05:00.719 --> 01:05:04.840
if you're in a SAS shop or an SPSS shop or what have you,

01:05:04.840 --> 01:05:06.639
having ultimately a champion

01:05:06.639 --> 01:05:08.760
who is in some form of a leadership role,

01:05:08.760 --> 01:05:09.719
you know, start identifying,

01:05:09.719 --> 01:05:13.080
I would say if you are in a leadership position,

01:05:13.080 --> 01:05:14.040
then you have the opportunity

01:05:14.040 --> 01:05:16.120
to start pushing that conversation.

01:05:16.120 --> 01:05:18.080
Otherwise it helps to have someone

01:05:18.080 --> 01:05:19.360
who is in a leadership position,

01:05:19.360 --> 01:05:21.199
who is open to the idea of, you know,

01:05:21.199 --> 01:05:22.959
maybe we can do some things that are different.

01:05:22.959 --> 01:05:25.239
Maybe we can do some things that are,

01:05:25.239 --> 01:05:27.199
you know, can broaden our horizons here

01:05:27.199 --> 01:05:29.000
in terms of the technologies that we're using

01:05:29.000 --> 01:05:30.560
and get that champion.

01:05:30.560 --> 01:05:33.159
And we were able to use this idea of EBCOP

01:05:33.159 --> 01:05:35.600
as sort of that proxy for that champion.

01:05:35.600 --> 01:05:37.879
And we started getting people to talk about it.

01:05:37.879 --> 01:05:40.360
We started holding workshops on doing R

01:05:40.360 --> 01:05:42.679
and how to get people up to those skill levels

01:05:42.679 --> 01:05:45.560
and working with the Department of Health IT

01:05:45.560 --> 01:05:48.040
to get R installed on people's workstations

01:05:48.040 --> 01:05:50.239
so that they can actually start using R,

01:05:50.239 --> 01:05:52.239
which is how we were able to make some headway there

01:05:52.239 --> 01:05:55.679
in a place that has a lot of SAS users.

01:05:56.679 --> 01:05:58.679
But yeah, I think having a process

01:05:58.679 --> 01:05:59.959
where you have both a champion

01:05:59.959 --> 01:06:02.360
and a process to start enabling people

01:06:02.360 --> 01:06:04.879
are both gonna be the two critical steps for that.

01:06:05.800 --> 01:06:06.800
That's awesome.

01:06:06.800 --> 01:06:08.040
Thank you so much, Andy.

01:06:08.040 --> 01:06:09.959
I know you have to run to your next meeting,

01:06:09.959 --> 01:06:13.600
but really appreciate you sharing your insights with us

01:06:13.600 --> 01:06:15.879
and answering everyone's questions.

01:06:15.879 --> 01:06:17.959
I'm excited to see that Slack channel grow too

01:06:17.959 --> 01:06:21.800
and we can answer some of the unanswered ones there too.

01:06:21.800 --> 01:06:23.360
Yeah, thank you for the good questions.

01:06:23.360 --> 01:06:24.479
Really good questions.

01:06:26.159 --> 01:06:27.560
Thank you all for joining as well.

01:06:27.560 --> 01:06:29.000
Have a great rest of the day.

